The app glitching and you not being able to access it caused an intense sense of panic and anxiety. This is often referred to as "app separation anxiety" or "digital withdrawal." &#x20;

When the app came back online and you were able to access the service again, your body released stress-relieving hormones like endorphins and dopamine, leading to a feeling of intense relief. This can be similar to the high people experience when they use drugs.

These kinds of experiences might suggest that you have an unhealthy attachment to the app. This can lead to further negative effects including:&#x20;

1.  Increased stress and anxiety
2.  Reduced feelings of relaxation
3.  Smaller attention span
4.  Less satisfaction with life in general



If you feel that your use of this app is negatively affecting your life in some of these ways, there are a few things that you can to in order to get things back under control.

1.  Set limits for yourself. Only allow yourself to log in one or two times a day.
2.  Remove the app from your home screen. This way it will be easier for you to not think about the app as much
3.  Take up hobbies and interests that give you a healthy escape from the world.&#x20;
4.  Seek out professional help from a therapist. Try to try and get somebody that specializes in app addiction.&#x20;
